CBRE Agribusiness is pleased to present for sale Kaladbro, a large scale grazing property located in South West Victoria.

Comprising approximately 2,632* hectares of contiguous land, key features of Kaladbro include:

- A substantial landholding that is currently utilised as a livestock finishing hub, with outstanding future development potential.

- Located close to the Port of Portland (84* radial kilometres), saleyards at Mount Gambier (25* radial kilometres) and Hamilton (90* radial kilometres) and processing facilities at Warrnambool (152* radial kilometres).

- Approximately 440 hectares of irrigable land, benefited by a 7,471* mega litre Ground Water Entitlement, with significant scope for further irrigation development.

- High quality soil types and excellent climatic characteristics (average annual rainfall of 690* millimetres).

- Operational improvements comprise an undercover sheep feedlot (6,200* head capacity), eight stand shearing shed, 750* tonnes of grain storage (comprising both silos and a grain shed), numerous sets of sheep and cattle yards and various machinery / hay / storage sheds.

- Original Homestead (in need of renovation) set within established gardens and featuring nine bedrooms, as well as four additional dwellings.

- Quality fencing, a well-designed laneway system and excellent stock water facilities.

CBRE Agribusiness is pleased to present for sale the Frances Farm Portfolio, comprising Frances, Minimay and Bool Lagoon (the Properties), three productive farms located in the Western Wimmera and South-East South Australia.

The Properties are located within a 75* lineal kilometre distance of each other and have a gross land area of 2,802* hectares, of which 1,275* hectares is developed to centre pivot irrigation.

Key investment highlights include:


FRANCES

- Total land area of 1,550* hectares, with 900* hectares developed to centre pivot irrigation, 575* hectares of dryland arable / grazing land, 70* hectares of Pine and Bluegum plantations and five* hectares of remnant vegetation.

- Four water licences, that are administered by Wimmera Mallee Water, with a total volume of 2,984* megalitres.

- Gently undulating in topography, Frances has historically been utilised for onion and potato production as well as fat lamb production, with dryland areas utilised for cropping (cereals and oilseeds) and comprises primarily grey sandy loams.

- Structural improvements include multiple dwellings and workers’ cottages, high clearance shedding utilised for horticultural produce sorting and storage, a mechanic’s workshop, office, hangar, wool shed, and ancillary shedding.

- A planning permit also exists allowing the use and development of a freestall barn dairy for a 3,600 cow milking herd.

MINIMAY

- Total land area of 647* hectares, with 120* hectares developed to centre pivot irrigation, 517* hectares of dryland arable / grazing land and 10* hectares of remnant vegetation.

- One water licence, administered by Wimmera Mallee Water, with a total volume of 400* megalitres.

- Gently undulating to rolling in topography, Minimay has been utilised primarily for cropping (cereals) and comprises and a mix of heavy dark sandy loams and lighter sandy loams.

- Structural improvements include a single dwelling, shearing shed and farm shedding.

BOOL LAGOON

-  Total land area of 605* hectares, with 260* hectares developed to centre pivot irrigation and 345* hectares of dryland arable / grazing land.

- Two water licences, within the Lower Limestone Coast Prescribed Wells Area (Hacks Management Area), with a total allocation of 1,390 megalitres for irrigation and 228 megalitres for specialised production requirements.

- Relatively flat in topography, Bool Lagoon has been utilised primarily for cropping and horticultural pursuits and comprises black clay loams over limestone with pivot areas having been rock picked and rolled.

- Structural improvements include a set of cattle yards and sheep yards.

MOKANGER (711 Mokanger Road, Cavendish 3314)

- Exceptional operational infrastructure, including a four-stand shearing shed with undercover yards (1,000* sheep capacity) and numerous storage / machinery / hay sheds.

- Improved pastures, high quality fencing, outstanding stock water infrastructure and a regimented fertiliser history.

LEWANA (1430 Dunkeld-Cavendish Road, Karabeal 3294)

- A 498* hectare grazing property comprising improved pastures, excellent stock water infrastructure, high quality fencing and a regimented fertiliser history.

- Excellent structural improvements and infrastructure, including a cottage, three-stand shearing shed, machinery shed, storage shed and recently upgraded cattle yards.

Mokanger and Lewana are being offered for sale in one line or as separate properties, including livestock, plant and equipment and feed on hand.

CBRE Agribusiness is privileged to present one of the Western District’s finest and most versatile historic holdings, meticulously presented, with quality infrastructure, ideally suited to its broad scale versatility.

Key features of the opportunity include:

LOCATION
- Ideally situated between Hamilton, Mortlake and Ballarat selling centres, only 30* minutes to the city of Hamilton and its excellent educational, shopping and financial services
- Major grain receival facilities are close by and major cities of Geelong and Melbourne are only 150km* and 200km* respectively.

LAND
- Gently rolling fertile grey and red sand loam soils
- The entire property is arable
- Soils are fertilized annually and identified pastures are renovated annually as required, to ensure maximum production
- Canola, red wheat, white wheat, barley and oats have all been grown with great success

WATER
- Significant 4ML* and 6ML* dams have been constructed, and water is reticulated throughout the property
- Many paddocks also have access to the permanent Hopkins River and Churrup Creek - the security of the water supply is a standout feature of Chatsworth House

CLIMATE
- Annual average rainfall of 550-600mm* per annum, is winter dominant, with true seasons
- A district renowned for its consistency and reliability, with proven winter crop yields, and recognized ability to fatten livestock

CURRENT USE
- 12,000* composite ewes are joined annually (lambing in June July), producing around 15,000* lambs per annum
- Up to 300 steers are grazed twice annually on the property, and pasture set aside for hay and silage
- ‘Chatsworth Prime’ has become a brand of choice for prime lamb retailers on the east coast of Australia

HOMESTEAD & IMPROVEMENTS
- Stunning 1,200* sqm Victorian Bluestone masterpiece set amidst a heritage, fully automated garden of English and native trees with inground solar heated swimming pool, private sweeping lawns and cascading symmetrical hedge lined rose gardens
- Comprising six bedrooms (three with ensuite), drawing room, billiards room, formal dining room, large country style kitchen, family room and cellar - all centrally heated
- Outbuildings comprise Bluestone Baronial hall with commercial kitchen, and refurbished accommodation
- Fully renovated Bluestone stables and coach houses
- Two Manager’s residences and four country style cottages
- 11 stand woolshed (1600* woollies), experts room, and full shearers facilities with staff kitchen
- Substantial undercover animal handling facilities, incorporating bugle yards, crush and loading ramp
- Machinery and hay shedding, fully equipped workshop and office complex

Chatsworth House is a meticulously presented enterprise, expertly managed, with a proven productive history of prime lambs, beef and cropping. This Western District icon is a rare example of the affluence of pastoral Australia, offering consistent income streams and an enviable lifestyle in a reliable, highly sought-after location.
